Placing the stops too close to these zones ain't clever, these are targeted to create liquidity and fill big orders. The main goal of these zones is to generate liquidity for a continuation or a rejection of the trend. 5/
It’s quite common for professional and retail traders alike to use swing highs/lows as logical places to place stops and/or reversal orders. 4/
The market does not work off of precise levels and exact prices: levels can often be better thought of as “zones,” extending 10-20 pips around a given price point. 3/

This is helpful for managing open trades, initiating new trades, and adjusting stop losses. While it’s impossible to avoid losses in the market, it is important to understand the where and why of the market’s reaction. 2/

Though It's fine to have it and to use divergences as a confirmation for your setup. 5/
-> So yeah it predicts a lot of reversals but most of them don't occur, giving you false positive signals if you rely on it heavily. 4/

- They usually occur when there is a sharp movement in a short amount of time, followed then by a less sharp movement. Divergences basically catch that, and in believing firmly in it, you believe that the price will reverse based on the fact that the movement slowed down. 3/
Example: Divergences can show sell signal on multiple TF (daily and H4) but the price can still climb up another 300-600 points. 2/
Why i don't rely on divergence as a leading indicator : - Divergence is how Oscillator catching up with price -> it has zero bearing on price. 1/
